The isReal() function on a String will return true if the number if an integer or a real number. I would expect it to only return true for numbers with a decimal place.

1 is integer=true
1 is real=true
1.0 is integer=false
1.0 is real=true
1.1 is integer=false
1.1 is real=true


===============================

var num := "1";
(num + " is integer=" + num.isInteger()).println();
(num + " is real=" + num.isReal()).println();

num := "1.0";
(num + " is integer=" + num.isInteger()).println();
(num + " is real=" + num.isReal()).println();

num := "1.1";
(num + " is integer=" + num.isInteger()).println();
(num + " is real=" + num.isReal()).println();

This is the expected behaviour so that EOL is consistent with Java in this respect. A workaround for checking that x is a genuine real could be the following:

operation String isRealReal() : Boolean {
  return self.isReal() and not self.isInteger();
}

Created attachment 192574
Patch which fixes the issue

If an EVL script only reports warnings, failOnErrors is set to true and failOnWarnings is set to false, the build fails, and it shouldn't.

This is because of the following code in EvlTask:

if (errors > 0 || warnings > 0) {
  fail((errors + " error(s) and " + warnings
       + " warning(s) found during validation"), null);
}

As you can see, it always fails: it doesn't tell apart the case when only warnings are reported. I've attached a patch which fixes this issue.

We already have literal expressions for Sequences, Bags, OrderedSets and so on, but we don't have one for Map objects. In the upcoming version of EUnit, we currently do something like this:

$with Sequence {"", "A"}
@test
operation etc() {
  -- ...
}

In the $with annotation, we intend to say 'the default model is A', but this meaning is hard to see, as we're using a Sequence instead of a Map. It would be easier to read with a Map literal expression, like this:

$with Map {"" = "A"}
@test
operation etc() {
  -- ...
}

After talking with Dimitris, we'd like to use "=" instead of ":" (à la Python) or "=>" (à la Perl) as key-value separator, in order to stay closer to OCL and its Tuples. However, this may introduce ambiguities in the grammar. How should we interpret "Map { 1 = 2 = 3 }"? Should it have one (false, 3) pair, or one (1, false) pair?

