Is there anything new on this Bug?

This has been now fixed in the SVN. To turn on XMI IDs for a model M, you need to add the following line in your code:

M.resource.useXmiIds = true;

I thought that this would be a better idea than to change the EMF model configuration dialog / ANT task, as this option is specific to XMI-based models (i.e. not Xtext/EmfText or XML-based models). If this sounds reasonable, I'll release a new interim version shortly.

At present, HUTN permits statements which mix reference and containment values in the same slot.

For example:

Family "The Smiths" {
  members: Person "John" {}, Person "Jane"
}

Person "Jane" {}

As a slot must be either a reference slot or a containment slot, this causes an exception to be raised during the transformation from AST to Intermediate model.

For this Ecore model:

class Person {
  attr String[0..1] name;
}

and this EOL:

var p = new Person;
p.name = 'Louis';
p.name = null;

p.name.println();
p.name.isDefined();

will print:
Louis
true

Operations should be able to access the out variable. The following, for example, throws an exception right now:

[%  setup() %]
[% operation setup() {
	out.setContentType("XML");
} %]

I have observed that all empty Sequence values seem to share the same set of extended properties. For instance, the following test case fails, as y.~extended seems to have been initialized when "x.~extended = 1" was executed:

@test
operation testExtendedPropertyAssignmentUsesIdentity() {
  var x : Sequence;
  var y : Sequence;
  x.~extended = 1;
  assertEquals(1, x.~extended);
  assertTrue(y.~extended.isUndefined());
}

Looking at the code, it seems that the issue is in EolContext, which uses a HashMap instead of an IdentityHashMap for the mapping from an object to its extended properties. HashMap uses the hashCode() function, which is based on the actual contents. Two empty sequences have the same hashCode(), so they end up sharing the extended properties as well.

I believe this is not the wanted behaviour, as it will likely surprise most users and may be a problem if we have different sequences with different meanings that somehow end up having the same literal elements.

Thanks for your insightful comments! I've now changed Real so that it is backed by a double instead of a float and added a field in EolReal called "doublePrecision" to let the engine know if the Real is a float or a double. I've also changed the grammar so that it supports "f" and "d" suffixes in Real literals to denote float and double values respectively. To preserve compatibility, if a suffix is not defined, the value is assumed to be a float. 

A short example follows:

(1.0).checkType('Float').println();
(1.0 + 1).checkType('Float').println();
(1 + 1).checkType('Integer').println();
(1.0d + 1.0f).checkType('Double').println();
(1.0f + 1.0f).checkType('Float').println();
(1.0f + 1).checkType('Float').println();
(1.0d + 1.0d).checkType('Double').println();

1.0d.asFloat().checkType('Float').println();
1.0f.asReal().checkType('Double').println();

operation Real checkType(expected : String) : Boolean {
	var type := '';
	if (self.isTypeOf(Integer)) {
		type := 'Integer';
	}
	else if (self.isDoublePrecision()) {
		type := 'Double';
	}
	else {
		type := 'Float';
	}
	return type = expected;
}

If this sounds good and there are no obvious defects, I can try to do the same with integers and long numbers...

